Path: Additional Language Notes
Content:
Recommended for use as a missing value indicator.
Commands that explicitly do not return a value (such as 
``print``
 or 
``if``
) return 
``null``
.
Commands that do not accept pipeline input have an input signature of 
``nothing``
.
``null``
 is similar to JSON's "null". However, whenever Nushell would print the 
``null``
 value (outside of a string or data structure), it prints nothing instead.
Example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> null | to json

null

> "null" | from json

# => no output

```
You can add 
``ignore``
 at the end of a pipeline to convert any pipeline result to a 
``nothing``
. This will prevent the command/pipeline's output from being displayed.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
git checkout featurebranch | ignore

```
It's important to understand that 
``null``
 is not the same as the absence of a value! It is possible for a table or list to have 
missing
 values. Missing values are displayed with a вќЋ character in interactive output.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> let missing_value = [{a:1 b:2} {b:1}]

> $missing_value

в•­в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•®

в”‚ # в”‚ a  в”‚ b в”‚

в”њв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¤

в”‚ 0 в”‚  1 в”‚ 2 в”‚

в”‚ 1 в”‚ вќЋ в”‚ 1 в”‚

в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв•Ї

```
By default, attempting to access a missing value will not produce 
``null``
 but will instead generate an error:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> let missing_value = [{a:1 b:2} {b:1}]

> $missing_value.1.a

Error: nu::shell::column_not_found


  Г— Cannot find column 'a'

  в•­в”Ђ[entry #4:1:32]

1 в”‚ let missing_value = [{a:1 b:2} {b:1}]

  В·                                в”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђ

  В·                                  в•°в”Ђв”Ђ value originates here

  в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ

  в•­в”Ђ[entry #6:1:18]

1 в”‚ $missing_value.1.a

  В·                  в”¬

  В·                  в•°в”Ђв”Ђ cannot find column 'a'

  в•°в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ

```
To safely access a value that may be missing, mark the cell-path member as 
optional
 using a question-mark (
``?``
) after the key name.

See 
[link: /book/navigating_structured_data.html#handling-missing-data] Navigating and Accessing Structured Data - Handling Missing Data
 for more details and examples.
